there and makes
his point.

30:46.945 --> 30:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you're not
saying we're
at that point now, are you?

30:49.581 --> 30:54.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAMESH PONNURU: I'm not. but I'm
saying that
even if Clinton does very well
in South Carolina,

30:54.653 --> 30:57.589 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it just causes him to go back to
protest mode.

30:57.689 --> 31:02.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It doesn't mean that he's -- I
think there
is no reason for him to drop out
because he's

31:02.527 --> 31:06.398 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
angling for a Cabinet
appointment in the Clinton
administration, the way a normal
primary candidate

31:06.498 --> 31:07.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
would be.

31:07.966 --> 31:10.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Two quick points
to support
Ramesh's central point.

31:10.469 --> 31:16.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First is that Democrats have
proportional
representation. So, Bernie
Sanders, with 40

31:16.908 --> 31:22.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
percent of the delegates at the
Democratic
Convention, and if that's the
case in Philadelphia,

31:22.681 --> 31:25.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what does he want? Does he want
a platform?
Does he want Hillary Clinton...

31:25.784 --> 31:27.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Because you
expect him to win
some contests.

31:27.619 --> 31:28.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Oh, I expect him
to win.

31:28.620 --> 31:30.388 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: More contests.

31:30.489 --> 31:32.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Even if it goes
the best way
for Clinton from this point
forward, yes,

31:32.824 --> 31:35.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I do think he will win states
and he will
surprise us.

31:35.827 --> 31:42.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I say that because this
gives him enormous
leverage, and he does -- and the
other -- second

31:42.801 --> 31:48.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thing is, you already see Senate
candidates,
Democratic Senate candidates
echoing and mimicking

31:49.074 --> 31:54.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
his words and his issues,
talking about the
economy being rigged in the very
language

31:54.646 --> 31:56.381 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that Bernie Sanders has used.

31:56.481 --> 32:02.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So he's already having an impact
and an influence
far beyond what anybody
expected, perhaps

32:02.387 --> 32:04.156 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
even himself, when this began.

32:04.256 --> 32:08.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Coming out of her
Nevada win
last weekend, Ramesh, Bernie
Sanders says

32:08.360 --> 32:13.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
words to the effect, Hillary
Clinton is already
adopting some of what we
believe, so that's

32:13.498 --> 32:14.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
already taking place.

32:14.866 --> 32:16.635 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RAMESH PONNURU: That's right.

32:16.735 --> 32:19.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's talked about having a
public option
in health care again. And that
is, I think,

32:19.471 --> 32:21.173 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Sanders influence.

32:21.273 --> 32:25.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ramesh Ponnuru,
Mark Shields,
it couldn't get any more
exciting than it

32:25.510 --> 32:29.014 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is right now. Thank you both.

32:29.114 --> 32:31.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Judy.

32:32.083 --> 32:35.554 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAMESH PONNURU: Thanks for
having me.

32:35.654 --> 32:38.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you, Judy.

32:38.657 --> 32:44.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: An election was
also center
stage in Iran today. Voters
streamed to the

32:44.362 --> 32:49.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
polls in a high-stakes contest
with far-reaching
consequences.

32:49.134 --> 32:54.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turnout was so heavy that voting
was extended
more than five hours past the
original closing

32:54.840 --> 32:55.540 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
time.

32:55.640 --> 32:57.442 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has the story.

32:57.542 --> 33:01.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It's an
election that could
shape Iran for years to come.
Millions of

33:01.746 --> 33:04.883 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people crowded into some 53,000
polling stations.

33:04.983 --> 33:09.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): One
shouldn't
be indifferent. I vote for the
future of our

33:09.454 --> 33:11.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country and for a higher level
of our welfare.

33:11.690 --> 33:17.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: They're
deciding who wins
the 290 seats in Parliament,
plus the 88 positions

33:17.696 --> 33:23.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Assembly of Experts, a
group of clerics
that chooses the country's
supreme leader.

33:23.301 --> 33:28.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There were multiple appeals
today to get out
the vote. The current supreme
leader, 76-year-old

33:28.740 --> 33:34.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, has been
in power
since 1989, and represents
conservative hard-liners.

33:34.346 --> 33:36.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AYATOLLAH ALI KHAMENEI, Supreme
Leader of
Iran (through translator): We
have enemies

33:36.948 --> 33:41.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are eying us greedily.
Turnout in the
elections should be as such that
our enemy

33:41.486 --> 33:46.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will be disappointed and will
lose hope. People
should be observant and vote
with open eyes.

33:46.858 --> 33:51.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: A vetting
panel, appointed
partly by Khamenei, had blocked
thousands

33:51.429 --> 33:56.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of reformist candidates from
running for Parliament,
and about 80 percent of those
running for

33:56.401 --> 33:58.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Assembly of Experts.

33:58.370 --> 34:03.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the more-moderate forces,
led by President
Hassan Rouhani, hoped to chip
away at hard-line

34:03.875 --> 34:05.677 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dominance.

34:05.777 --> 34:07.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HASSAN ROUHANI, Iranian
President (through
translator): Today, our friends
and enemies

34:07.679 --> 34:12.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from around the world are gazing
at Islamic
Iran. I have no doubt that the
Iranian nation,

34:12.617 --> 34:17.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like always, will create another
epic turnout
at this very sensitive juncture
in time.

34:17.756 --> 34:22.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The vote is,
to some degree,
a referendum on Rouhani's
promises of greater

34:22.994 --> 34:26.097 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
freedoms and economic reform.

34:26.197 --> 34:30.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's also the first election
since the nuclear
deal with the U.S. and other
world powers

34:30.702 --> 34:35.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
signed last summer. Under the
agreement, Iran
is curbing its nuclear program,
in exchange

34:35.907 --> 34:38.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for international sanctions
relief.

34:38.743 --> 34:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just today, the U.N.'s nuclear
watchdog found
Tehran is mostly complying with
the deal so

34:43.848 --> 34:49.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
far. The election outcome is
also being closely
watched in Washington. Full
election returns

34:50.021 --> 34:52.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are not expected until early
next week.

34:52.257 --> 34:57.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me now for more on the
Iranian elections
and what may come next is Thomas
Erdbrink.

34:58.096 --> 35:01.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the Tehran bureau chief for
The New York
Times.

35:01.166 --> 35:06.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thomas, we have heard several
headlines today
that the polls have been full of
people, the

35:06.871 --> 35:09.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lines have been long and that
they're extending
voting. What have you seen on
the ground?

35:10.075 --> 35:14.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS ERDBRINK, The New York
Times: That's
definitely what I have seen as
well, especially

35:14.279 --> 35:17.716 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the more middle-class areas
of Tehran.

35:17.816 --> 35:22.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You should know that Tehran is a
city of 12
million people, has a lot of
different areas,

35:22.354 --> 35:28.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but up in the north and the west
of the city,
you could see long lines at each
polling station

35:28.193 --> 35:33.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
almost throughout the day, from
the morning
all the way up to the evening.
There were

35:33.365 --> 35:39.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
four extensions in some areas,
so people over
there really wanted to go out
and vote.

35:39.104 --> 35:47.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when you would go down to
the south of
Tehran, where more poorer people
live, you

35:47.312 --> 35:52.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would see a different picture,
half-empty
polling stations, maybe
half-a-dozen people

35:52.917 --> 35:57.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
around casting their ballots.
So, there was
a big divide in Tehran.

35:57.155 --> 36:02.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, I have no idea
what it, nationwide,
looked like, but at least one
thing is for

36:02.861 --> 36:07.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sure. There was a very high
turnout among
Tehran's middle classes, the
same people who

36:08.033 --> 36:12.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have supported President Rouhani
in the past
and are clearly, by voting in
this parliamentary

36:13.071 --> 36:15.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
elections, also trying to
support him now.

36:15.673 --> 36:18.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We have also
heard that
this is not -- this is certainly
not like

36:18.710 --> 36:23.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an American election, and that
there has already
been a pre-selection of who is
allowed to

36:23.448 --> 36:26.384 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
run for many of the open seats.

36:26.484 --> 36:32.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
THOMAS ERDBRINK: Well, of
course, it's always
hard to compare elections
worldwide, but,

36:32.257 --> 36:34.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
yes, it is definitely true.

36:34.192 --> 36:40.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a clerical council that
is half elected
by the people indirectly and
half appointed

36:40.498 --> 36:48.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Supreme Leader Khamenei. And
they have
disqualified around 6,000 out of
12,000 candidates

36:48.173 --> 36:53.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for these two elections that the
Iranians
have been voting for today on
Friday.

36:53.711 --> 36:59.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These people are the gatekeepers
of Iran's
electoral process. And what they
look at is

36:59.551 --> 37:07.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if someone is loyal to the
principles of the
ideology of the Islamic
Republic, if you will,

37:07.292 --> 37:09.260 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and also if he or she is a good
Muslim.

37:09.360 --> 37:14.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, of course, this also gives
space for
certain political groups not to
have the presence

37:14.766 --> 37:19.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they would like to have in
the political
process. And this is what
happens to the country's

37:19.737 --> 37:25.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reformists, who saw thousands of
their candidates
actually being disqualified,
but, at the same

37:26.010 --> 37:30.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time, their candidates that were
allowed to
run today called upon people to
massively

37:30.315 --> 37:33.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go out and vote, which their
supporters actually
did.

37:33.651 --> 37:39.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Even with
these constraints
that the clerical council puts
on this process,

37:39.324 --> 37:42.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what are the moderates or the
reformists hoping
to accomplish?

37:42.827 --> 37:50.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS ERDBRINK: This election
is just a stop
in the long road of fighting, if
you will,

37:50.301 --> 37:58.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
political fighting between
people we could
refer to as reformists vs.,
let's say, hard-liners.

37:59.010 --> 38:04.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this fight has been going
on for decades,
and the reformers in the last 10
years, in

38:04.349 --> 38:09.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all honesty, have almost lost
every time.
Now, what they have been trying
to achieve

38:10.088 --> 38:15.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is to make sure that as many of
their supporters,
of the reformer supporters came
out and voted

38:15.960 --> 38:24.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
today in order to prevent these
hard-liners
from keeping their grip on the
Parliament.

38:24.636 --> 38:30.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what reformist leaders have
been telling
me is actually, any seat we can
win from the

38:30.708 --> 38:32.977 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hard-liners is a victory for us.

38:33.077 --> 38:36.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Thomas Erdbrink,
Tehran bureau chief of The New
York Times,

38:36.714 --> 38:37.582 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
thanks so much for joining us.

38:37.682 --> 38:42.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
THOMAS ERDBRINK: Thanks for
having me.

38:42.287 --> 38:58.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The Academy
Awards will be
given out this Sunday. But
instead of the

38:58.303 --> 39:04.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nominees, much of the focus this
year is on,
as the hashtag on Twitter has
it, Oscars so

39:04.876 --> 39:08.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
white, and Hollywood's lack of
diversity.

39:08.479 --> 39:10.515 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown has more.

39:10.615 --> 39:15.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Richard Pryor at
the Academy
Awards in 1977:

39:15.887 --> 39:24.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD PRYOR, Comedian: I'm
here to explain
why no black people will ever be
nominated

39:24.229 --> 39:25.363 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for anything.

39:25.463 --> 39:26.364 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

39:26.464 --> 39:29.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Chris Rock 28
years later.

39:29.267 --> 39:35.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS ROCK, Comedian: We have
four black nominees
tonight. So, great. It's kind of
like the

39:35.640 --> 39:37.041 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Def Oscar Jam tonight.

39:37.141 --> 39:38.910 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

39:39.010 --> 39:43.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In some ways,
Hollywood's lack
of diversity is an old story,
but as Rock

39:43.781 --> 39:50.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prepares to host his second
Oscar ceremony,
and for a second straight year,
no actors

39:50.521 --> 39:55.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of color were nominated, the
stakes and anger
have risen, including calls for
a boycott

39:56.060 --> 39:57.895 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the event.

39:57.996 --> 40:00.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JADA PINKETT SMITH, Actress: I
will not be
at the Academy Awards, and I
won't be watching.

40:00.331 --> 40:05.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Academy of
Motion Pictures,
the group that oversees and
votes on nominations,

40:05.803 --> 40:11.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
announced new rules to develop a
younger,
more diverse Oscar voting pool,
the aim, double

40:11.542 --> 40:14.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the number of female and
minority members
by 2020.

40:14.746 --> 40:16.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But many see the problem as much
deeper.

40:17.081 --> 40:19.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SPIKE LEE, Director: It goes
further than
the Academy Awards. It has to go
back to the

40:19.917 --> 40:20.752 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
gatekeepers.

40:20.852 --> 40:22.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE STEPHANOPOULOS, ABC News:
Studios.

40:22.186 --> 40:24.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SPIKE LEE: Yes, the people who
have the green-light
vote.

40:24.322 --> 40:31.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IDRIS ELBA, Actor: Talent is
everywhere, but
opportunity isn't. Talent can't
reach opportunity

40:31.229 --> 40:33.031 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
unaided.

40:33.131 --> 40:40.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Idris Elba, whose
performance
in "Beasts of No Nation" was
widely praised,

40:40.772 --> 40:43.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
recently spoke of roadblocks he
faced early
in his career.

40:43.508 --> 40:49.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IDRIS ELBA: I realized I could
only play so
many best friends or gang
leaders. Right?

40:49.180 --> 40:54.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I knew that I wasn't going to
land a leading
role. I knew there wasn't enough
imagination,

40:54.185 --> 40:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not yet, for the industry to be
seeing me
as a lead.

40:59.023 --> 41:05.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In recent years,
television
has presented more diverse
programming, hit

41:05.563 --> 41:09.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shows like "Orange Is the New
Black" and "Jane
the Virgin."

41:09.267 --> 41:14.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And just last week, ABC made
Channing Dungey,
who helped develop shows like
"Black-ish,"

41:15.039 --> 41:22.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the first African-American to
head a network.
But it was only last year that
Viola Davis

41:22.380 --> 41:27.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
became the first black woman to
win an Emmy
for best actress in a drama
series.

41:27.919 --> 41:29.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She spoke of the obstacles.

41:29.687 --> 41:33.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VIOLA DAVIS, Actress: You cannot
win an Emmy
for roles that are simply not
there.

41:33.691 --> 41:40.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: How host Chris
Rock will address
all of this is now part of the
fun and seriousness

41:40.498 --> 41:41.599 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of Sunday night's ceremony.

41:41.699 --> 41:43.534 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRIS ROCK: Let's do this.

41:43.634 --> 41:46.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And we look at
the situation
and the potential way forward
now with Darnell

41:47.004 --> 41:52.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hunt, professor of sociology at
UCLA and co-author
of an annual report on Hollywood
diversity,

41:52.844 --> 41:57.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Alex Nogales, president of the
National Hispanic
Media Coalition, which advocates
for more

41:57.415 --> 42:03.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inclusive representation of
Latinos in film
and TV, and Sharon Waxman,
founder of The

42:03.154 --> 42:07.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wrap, a news site covering the
entertainment
and media industries.

42:07.492 --> 42:08.960 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And welcome to all three of you.

42:09.060 --> 42:10.828 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I want to start with you,
Darnell Hunt.

42:10.928 --> 42:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And help us first briefly define
the problem
and what you see as its source.

42:16.300 --> 42:19.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARNELL HUNT, Professor of
Sociology, UCLA:
Well, what we're dealing with is
a disconnect

42:19.971 --> 42:24.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between, on the one hand, the
increasing diversity
of American society -- we're
almost 40 percent

42:24.742 --> 42:31.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
minority -- on the other hand,
the fact that,
stubbornly, the industry just
can't seem to

42:31.115 --> 42:32.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
make diverse projects.

42:33.050 --> 42:36.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In our study, we find that, on
every front,
people of color and women are
underrepresented,

42:36.254 --> 42:41.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
behind the camera, in front of
the camera.
And yet we also see, from
audience consumption

42:41.259 --> 42:45.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
patterns, that people of color,
diverse audiences,
crave diverse content.

42:45.730 --> 42:49.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we have a situation where the
people who
are running the industry, and
largely white

42:49.534 --> 42:53.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
males, aren't in a position to
make the types
of projects that people want.
And that's the

42:53.671 --> 42:57.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fundamental issue. It's trying
to figure out
how to bring more people in the
room, how

42:57.241 --> 42:59.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to get more voices and
perspective into the
process.

42:59.744 --> 43:04.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so Alex
Nogales, tell
us how it plays out. You work
sometimes with

43:04.916 --> 43:10.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the experiences of Latinos and
others, what
kind of roles they get or don't
get, what

43:10.621 --> 43:13.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind -- what they run up against
as writers
or Directors.

43:13.458 --> 43:15.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALEX NOGALES, President,
National Hispanic
Media Coalition: Well, they
can't even get

43:16.093 --> 43:17.829 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

43:17.929 --> 43:21.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The opportunities are not there.
As Darnell
just said, the problem is that
you have 95

43:21.933 --> 43:27.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
percent whites in leadership
positions at
all of the studios, the six
studios here in

43:27.505 --> 43:35.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
town. And you have a majority of
them being
males. So, they rose up in the
ranks of this

43:35.713 --> 43:41.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whole thing called film, and
they have made
their alliances, they have made
their friendships,

43:41.819 --> 43:43.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
they have made their
relationships.

43:43.821 --> 43:49.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so when it's time to call
for a new product,
that's who they call in, other
people that

43:50.061 --> 43:55.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are like them, that are white,
that are male,
and so forth. And the reflection
then doesn't

43:55.399 --> 44:00.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
include us. The jobs are not
there because
the people at the very top are
not making

44:01.038 --> 44:04.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the decisions that are ones of
inclusion.

44:04.308 --> 44:08.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, Sharon
Waxman, is that
the industry you see, that you
cover every

44:08.880 --> 44:15.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
day? Is it about who you know?
Is it about
overt racism or sexism? Is it
all about money?

44:15.987 --> 44:17.788 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
What?

44:17.889 --> 44:19.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHARON WAXMAN, Editor in Chief,
TheWrap.Com:
Well, I think it's worse than
that because

44:19.857 --> 44:25.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you have a culturally very
liberal entertainment
industry, famously so, in which
people are

44:25.463 --> 44:29.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
politically very much to the
left. You see
that in some of the programming
choices and

44:29.967 --> 44:33.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the messages, whether it's
Norman Lear for
so many years and the television
that he wrote

44:33.604 --> 44:39.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that heavily influenced American
society in
the '70s, or whether you see
that with "Will

44:39.710 --> 44:46.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
&amp; Grace" or shows like -- shows
like that
that push the needle forward on
social issues

44:46.717 --> 44:48.519 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all the time.

44:48.619 --> 44:56.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it is true that the issue of
decision-makers
being primarily white and male,
with some

44:56.561 --> 45:01.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
notable exceptions, has been the
case. I do
think that this is essentially a
small community

45:02.066 --> 45:06.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of people who come up together,
who call on
their friends. If you are in a
studio job

45:06.237 --> 45:10.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and you leave a studio job, you
become a producer,
and your buddy then calls you up
and asks

45:10.474 --> 45:12.410 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you for your latest pitches.

45:12.510 --> 45:21.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it has to be more thoughtful,
significant
and proactive effort to change
that.

45:21.118 --> 45:25.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so, Darnell
Hunt, as
a sociologist, you are studying
individuals

45:25.990 --> 45:31.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
within institutions. Right? And
this is a
primary example. Do you see
successes? Do

45:31.796 --> 45:37.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you see places where there has
been progress
made, potential models?

45:37.335 --> 45:39.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DARNELL HUNT: Yes, I think there
are lots
of models.

45:39.904 --> 45:44.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The successes, though,
unfortunately, are
the exceptions to the rule.
Business as usual

45:44.709 --> 45:50.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the industry, as our report
shows, our
2016 report shows, is more of
the same. It's

45:50.114 --> 45:53.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under-representation for people
of color and
women.

45:53.517 --> 45:58.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABC's move, I think, was a very
bold move,
but it made business sense. This
woman had

45:58.489 --> 46:02.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
been the executive vice
president for drama
development. And she was the
person who's

46:02.126 --> 46:05.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
responsible for a lot of those
Shonda Rhimes
shows that are doing really well
on ABC, as

46:05.730 --> 46:07.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
well as some of their other
prime-time dramas.

46:07.632 --> 46:13.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it just made sense for her
to become head
of that network because of the
network she

46:13.604 --> 46:17.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has and the connections she has
with the creative
community. And it's
forward-thinking. It's

46:17.775 --> 46:22.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
looking at where America is
going. And I think
a lot of ABC's programming kind
of gestures

46:22.813 --> 46:24.548 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
toward that present and that
future.

46:24.649 --> 46:28.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think that other networks
and studios
need to get into this game as
well.

46:28.119 --> 46:31.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Alex Nogales,
continue that
forward thinking for us, if you
would. When

46:31.689 --> 46:36.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you go to the studio, what are
you saying?
What are you asking for? What's
the pitch?

46:36.794 --> 46:44.602 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALEX NOGALES: In the year
2000-2001, the Multi-Ethnic
Media Coalition signed
memorandums of understanding

46:44.702 --> 46:51.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with ABC, NBC, CBS and FOX. And
for us, that's
a model that we're going to
utilize with the

46:51.709 --> 46:53.477 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
six studios.

46:53.577 --> 46:57.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the reason for that is
because it's working.
It is working slowly, but it's
working.

46:57.615 --> 47:01.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What does it say?
Tell us specifically,
what does that mean?

47:01.352 --> 47:05.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEX NOGALES: That they're going
to diversify
their work force both in front
and in back

47:05.856 --> 47:10.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of camera. They're going to give
you -- they're
going to give us the actual
numbers of who

47:10.561 --> 47:15.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is working in front and in back
of camera,
and that we are going to be
partners in this

47:15.766 --> 47:18.936 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
enterprise of diversifying the
work force.

47:19.036 --> 47:23.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's working on television
slowly, but it's
working. Now we have to make it
work as well

47:24.075 --> 47:25.810 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in film.

47:25.910 --> 47:29.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, Sharon
Waxman, to the extent
that this is an old issue, is it
possible

47:29.880 --> 47:36.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to tell yet how much of an
impact all the
most recent kind of anger and
uproar has had

47:36.687 --> 47:37.555 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or might have?

47:37.655 --> 47:39.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SHARON WAXMAN: Right.

47:39.557 --> 47:44.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and
Sciences, which governs the
Oscars, has adopted

47:44.729 --> 47:53.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very significant changes in the
wake of this
latest protest. They are going
to try to double

47:53.237 --> 47:58.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the number of minorities and
women in the
Academy voting membership by the
year 2020,

47:58.175 --> 48:03.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they're phasing out people
who haven't
been active in the Academy -- or
in the industry

48:03.280 --> 48:05.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- sorry -- for the past 10
years.

48:05.716 --> 48:09.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know if that's going to
really make
the change that they need. This
really means

48:10.087 --> 48:14.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they need to admit a lot of
people of color
and a lot of women over the next
five years.

48:15.092 --> 48:21.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You need to find those qualified
people. People
do want to see change, but there
is no stakeholder

48:21.665 --> 48:27.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with power within the industry
that has the
wherewithal to drive that
change.

48:27.138 --> 48:31.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they always end up being
kind of window
dressing. So, I would be curious
to see. I

48:31.142 --> 48:35.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would be -- hope, for Alex
Nogales' sake and
for all of our sakes, that those
agreements

48:36.080 --> 48:39.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that he signed really do lead to
substantive
change.

48:39.683 --> 48:44.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I do think that public
shaming is not
a bad way to do that, which is
what has happened

48:44.255 --> 48:50.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this year. But, ultimately,
these are media
companies that answer to their
shareholders,

48:50.194 --> 48:54.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so we can't -- we have to make
an economic
argument for that. And I think
there is a

48:54.298 --> 48:56.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
strong economic argument for
that.

48:56.233 --> 49:00.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Darnell Hunt,
just a brief
last word. Are you hopeful as
this point as

49:00.738 --> 49:02.540 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we prepare to watch the Oscars?

49:02.640 --> 49:05.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DARNELL HUNT: Well, you know,
I'm a cautious
optimist. I think we have to
keep applying

49:05.709 --> 49:07.478 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the pressure.

49:07.578 --> 49:10.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no magic bullet. We
have to approach
this from every front. The
economic argument

49:10.181 --> 49:15.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a strong one. Our study shows
inconclusive
-- I mean, shows conclusively
that, you know,

49:15.452 --> 49:17.254 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
diversity sells.

49:17.354 --> 49:20.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Audiences of color are craving
that content,
and shows that are diverse, on
average, do

49:20.724 --> 49:25.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
better on ratings and movies do
better at
the box office. So, we just have
to keep amassing

49:25.596 --> 49:29.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the data. It's there, and it's
only going
to become more profound as time
goes on, as

49:29.934 --> 49:31.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the population becomes more
diverse.

49:31.869 --> 49:35.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Darnell Hunt,
Alex Nogales,
and Sharon Waxman, thank you,
all three, very

49:35.639 --> 49:36.173 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

49:36.273 --> 49:36.941 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DARNELL HUNT: Thank you.

49:37.041 --> 49:38.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALEX NOGALES: Thank you.

